# Local audit / handoff workspaces — produced during development, not part
# of the shipped plugin. Each release leaves bundles under magi-audit-*/
# from local self-review runs; .remember/ is a per-session handoff buffer.
# Future telemetry snapshots that should ship (e.g. for the 2026-05-15
# review routine) must live in a path that does not match these entries
# or be force-added with `git add -f`.
.remember/
magi-audit-2.1.1/
magi-audit-2.1.2/
magi-audit-postfix/
.regression/

# Premortem experiment artifacts live on a local-only feature branch
# (see CLAUDE.md "Post-release hardening / Premortem A/B experiment").
# The directory persists on disk after branch checkout to main until the
# operator deletes both the branch and the directory on 2026-05-29.
experiments/

# Local developer tooling (SBTDD/graphify/usage-gate helpers from
# BolivarTech/AI_Tools). Referenced by CLAUDE.local.md but not part of the
# shipped plugin — each developer instantiates their own copy.
/scripts/claude_usage.py
/scripts/sleep_signal.py
/scripts/graphify_ollama.py
# Release tooling: network-bound (excluded from make verify) and for the maintainer,
# not the user. Its smoke test imports it, so that test is dev-local too: a fresh
# checkout without scripts/ simply never collects tests/test_release_tooling.py.
#
# NOTE: the v5 migration validator is NOT here. Every fail-closed v4 error, the README,
# the skill and docs/ollama-backend.md tell the USER to run it, so it is product and
# ships: skills/magi/scripts/validate_magi_toml.py (tests/test_validate_magi_toml.py).
/scripts/verify_fallback_tags.py
/tests/test_release_tooling.py

# Review-gate artifacts: bundles handed to MAGI (spec + plan + standards) and
# usage-gate snapshots. Local to a gate run, never part of the shipped plugin.
# A `git add -A` during a release swept a 7k-line bundle into a 19-line hotfix
# once; these entries are why it will not happen again.
#
# Anchored with a leading `/`: the bundles always live at the repo root, and an
# unanchored `magi-review-*.md` would match at ANY depth — silently swallowing a
# future *tracked* doc that happened to be named that way. A .gitignore that
# eats a file you meant to commit is worse than one that misses an artifact.
/checkpoint2-bundle.md
# Every extension, not just .md: the gate's diff was written as magi-review-<v>-diff.TXT,
# the pattern below only matched .md, and a `git add -A` swept a 312 KB review artifact into
# the v5.1.0 tag. A pattern that covers the file you happen to name today and not the one you
# name tomorrow is a pattern that will be beaten by a file extension.
/magi-review-*
/smoke-bundles/
/claude-usage.txt

# R17a release-gate artifact (tools/measure_marker_adherence.py). It is EVIDENCE of a
# real, paid MAGI-run measurement -- attached to a GitHub Release, not the source tree --
# same reasoning that keeps magi-report.json audit bundles out of git. The script that
# PRODUCES and CHECKS it lives in tools/ and IS tracked (see that module's docstring for
# why: a tracked `make release-check` calling a gitignored script is the v5.0.3 bug).
/marker-adherence-report.json
magi-corpus/
